2026-04-21 01:39:57 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module internal lamp (main bulb)', 'load module internal wiring / series diode'] hypothesis_explanation='The power-supply LED is solidly on, and direct measurement at the control module’s output shows a steady ~12 V across the lines even during the moments when the main lamp goes dark. This proves that the power supply and ambient‑sensor/relay module are delivering a stable DC supply without the 20‑second interruptions observed at the lamp. Therefore the periodic half‑second outages must be occurring downstream of the control module, i.e., inside the load module.\n\nWithin the load module there are only the series diode and the two parallel lamps (indicator and main). The fault is intermittent (about every 20 s, lasting ~0.5 s) and clears on its own, with no evidence of supply fluctuation. The most probable causes are:\n- An internal intermittent open or high‑resistance connection in the main lamp (filament or socket) that occasionally breaks under thermal or mechanical stress, briefly interrupting current before reconnecting.\n- Less likely, an intermittent open in the load module’s internal wiring or the series diode that affects primarily the main lamp path, though this would typically also extinguish the indicator lamp if it shares the same series path.\n\nBecause the supply to the load module is stable and no other modules show faults, the root cause is best localized to the main lamp (and its immediate connections) within the load module. Replacing the main bulb and checking its socket/wiring and series diode is expected to eliminate the periodic flicker.'
