2026-04-21 01:40:33 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module control electronics (oscillator / comparator around light sensor and timing & sensitivity potentiometers)'] hypothesis_explanation='All supply rails from the power module are solid (LED on, ~11.85 V present). Measurements at the control module output show a steady 11.85 V and ~0 V, even while the main lamp in the load module goes dark for ~0.5 s every ~20 s. Relay contact measurements show essentially zero drop across the contacts and no change when the lamp blinks, proving the relay is firmly closed and not the source of the interruption. In the load module, both lamps and the series diode are healthy and the internal supply node voltages (before and after the diode and at the return) remain steady during the blink, so there is no true voltage interruption to the load. Yet visibly the main lamp extinguishes briefly. The simulator repeatedly reports an "unstable or oscillating state" particularly during adjustment of the timing potentiometer, implicating the control circuitry rather than passive wiring. The only remaining plausible explanation is that the analog control electronics in the ambient sensor module (the light‑sensor front‑end with its timing/sensitivity network and comparator/driver) are oscillating or intermittently modulating the effective drive, producing a perceptible 0.5 s drop in lamp brightness even though the DC voltage appears steady at the simple measurement points. Replacing/repairing the control module’s internal control electronics (oscillator/comparator section) should remove the oscillation and stop the periodic lamp dropout.'
