2026-04-21 01:41:30 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ground / 0V reference wiring or layout between modules (shared return path causing oscillation)'] hypothesis_explanation='All active components (power supply, control electronics, relay contacts, lamps, diodes, and inter‑module cable polarities) have now been verified as healthy and correctly wired. The control module output stays at ~11.85 V and 0.02–0.03 V, and the load‑module internal voltages before and after its series diode remain steady even while the main symptom—a brief lamp extinguishing every ~20 s—is observed. The relay contacts show essentially zero voltage drop and do not open during the blink, and the lamps themselves have correct resistance and solid continuity. The battery is stable. \n\nThe only abnormal measurement is the existence of small but non‑zero DC offsets (10–45 mV) between what should be common 0 V reference nodes: power‑supply negative, the control module internal ground, and the load module negative return, with the simulator explicitly reporting an unstable/oscillating circuit state when these are probed. This indicates that the different modules are not sharing an ideal, low‑impedance common return; instead, there is an unintended resistance/inductance in the shared ground path or a subtle mis‑connection of the 0 V wiring that lets load current modulate the local ground potential. That kind of marginal ground integrity can make the control electronics and sensor threshold effectively see a slowly varying reference, creating a self‑oscillation where the control circuit briefly drives the lamp current low (or off) even though its nominal output node appears steady when measured against the battery negative.\n\nSince every individual component and explicit positive‑side connection has been ruled out and the only persistent anomaly is the inter‑module 0 V reference behavior and reported oscillation, the most plausible root cause is a fault in the common ground / 0 V wiring or layout between modules (e.g., a high‑resistance or shared return that couples the control electronics and load currents), rather than in any one discrete component already tested or replaced.'
