2026-04-21 01:42:03 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module series diode (forward drop / type mismatch or incorrect part value)'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules, cables, polarity, lamps, relay contacts, and grounds have now been individually tested and verified good, and previous hypotheses about intermittent wiring, sensor oscillation, and shared‑ground problems were disproven.\n\nKey remaining anomaly:\n• The control module output is at ~11.85 V relative to ground.\n• The internal lamp node (after the series diode in the load module) sits at ~11.06 V relative to ground.\n• This yields a persistent voltage drop of about 0.8 V across the series element between these two points.\n\nGiven the circuit description, the only component between the control module positive output terminal and the internal lamp node is the series protection diode in the load module. A healthy silicon power diode would be expected to drop ~0.6–0.7 V at the lamp current; 0.8 V is higher than normal and, more importantly, it is the *only* unexplained drop in the entire supply path. All other measurements show essentially zero drop across relay contacts and cabling.\n\nThe lamp’s brief 0.5 s turn‑off every ~20 s, with a simulator‑reported unstable/oscillating state, is consistent with a marginal or wrong‑type diode (e.g., an inappropriate part with excessive forward resistance or a device that partially enters thermal runaway). Under the lamp load, the diode may periodically heat such that its forward characteristics change enough for the lamp current to momentarily collapse, then recover as conditions change, creating the observed blinking while leaving DC voltages elsewhere apparently steady.\n\nSince the continuity and basic wiring around the diode have already been validated, the most plausible single‑component root cause that matches the measured 0.8 V differential and all other tests is a faulty or incorrect series diode inside the load module. Replacing that diode with the correct specified device should remove the excessive forward drop and instability and stop the periodic lamp turn‑off.'
